37872>>>    // Add code to customize your Zoom View based on how it was invoked.
37872>>>    // Use NavigateData to determine the context this view will be used in.
37872>>>    Procedure OnNavigateForward tWebNavigateData NavigateData Integer hoInvokingView Integer hoInvokingObject
37875>>>
37875>>>        // if this view is being used in multiple contexts, you may need a block of code
37875>>>        // like this to handle customizations. This would include hiding rows and buttons
37875>>>        // (WebSet pbRender) and changing the values of various captions.
37875>>>        Case Begin
37875>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromMain)
37877>>>                // If from main, this is a probably a main file Select to Zoom.
37877>>>                // This is the most typical way to navigate to a zoom.
37877>>>                Case Break
37878>>>                
37878>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromParent)
37881>>>                // If from parent, this is a constrained drill down.
37881>>>                // If needed, you could check NavigateData.iTable to determine the constraining parent.
37881>>>                // This would be unusual - normally you drill down from a parent to a list (Select view).
37881>>>                Case Break
37882>>>                
37882>>>            Case (NavigateData.eNavigateType = nfFromChild)
37885>>>                // If from child, this is a probably a parent Zoom from a Zoom. 
37885>>>                // This is unusual, but it might be used for adding a new child record.
37885>>>                Case Break
37886>>>                
37886>>>            Case Else // must be nfUndefined
37886>>>                // This may be the start of a query or this may be used for some kind of custom operation.
37886>>>                // You may want to check NavigateData.NamedValues.
37886>>>                  
37886>>>        Case End
37886>>>
37886>>>        // Action buttons can be changed dynamically during a Zoom's display lifetime.
37886>>>        // It's best to set these buttons in their own procedure so you can change later.
37886>>>        Send SetActionButtons
37887>>>
37887>>>    End_Procedure
37888>>>
37888>>>End_Object
